<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:16<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7206547682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:16.</label.designator><headtext>Forfeiture by wrongdoing</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017175" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-804" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I036cb9c074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-804(b)(5)</cite.query>, Georgia now recognizes a <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“forfeiture by wrongdoing”[<footnote.reference refid="I7a0dfd0074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] exception to the hearsay rule in that <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“[a] statement offered against a party that has engaged or acquiesced in wrongdoing that was intended to, and did, procure the unavailability of the declarant as a witness”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> shall not be excluded by the hearsay rule if the declarant is unavailable as a witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7a0dfd0174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017175" w-serial-number="2044331735" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I036e195274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Hendrix v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7a0dfd0274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference><?page no="307"?>] the Georgia Supreme Court upheld the admission of a transcript of an interview with police by the defendant&apos;s grandmother because she refused to testify at trial and refused to read her transcript. <eos/><bos/>The grandmother was threatened by the defendant, both via letter, where the defendant had written “snitch” on copies of her interview with the police, and verbally in the courthouse hallway before the trial started. <eos/><bos/>The Court adopted a three prong test: (1) the defendant engaged or acquiesced in the wrongdoing, (2) the wrongdoing was intended to procure the declarant&apos;s unavailability, and (3) the wrongdoing did procure the unavailability.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7a0dfd0074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017175" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER804" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I036d07e074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 804(b)(6)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017175" w-serial-number="2004190005" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I036d07e374d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Crawford v. Washington, 541 U.S. 36, 124 S. Ct. 1354, 158 L. Ed. 2d 177, 63 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 1077 (2004)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7a0dfd0174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017175" w-serial-number="2034800417" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I036d7d1274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Brittain v. State, 329 Ga. App. 689, 766 S.E.2d 106 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7a0dfd0274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017175" w-serial-number="2044331735" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I036e406274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hendrix v. State, 303 Ga. 525, 813 S.E.2d 339 (2018)</cite.query><?page no="307"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:16<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
